{
  "answer": "**Nārada Smṛti, Chapter 1** declares witnesses to be of exactly eleven kinds: five appointed (a written witness, a reminded witness, an accidental witness, a secret witness, and a subsequent witness) and six unappointed (the village, the chief judge, the king in the case of litigants, he who is involved in the business, he who is sent by the plaintiff, and the family in family disputes).[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Nārada Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-64e00d](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-64e00d).\n[^2]: Nārada Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-4ddcd7](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-4ddcd7).\n[^3]: Nārada Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-c777e2](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-c777e2).\n[^4]: Nārada Smṛti, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-3bf2a8](/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-3bf2a8).",
